":"1277","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1371":"1371","1280":"1280","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Aller, Dorset, England":"Aller, Dorset, England"},"en":{"1278–1330":"1278–1330","1277–Female":"1277–Deceased","1280–1298":"1280–1298","1298–1371":"1298–1371","1299–Male":"1299–Deceased","1245–1300":"1245–1300","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1299":"1299","1277":"1277","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1371":"1371","1280":"1280","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Aller, Dorset, England":"Aller, Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hatch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hatch (Bedfordshire, Devon, Hampshire, Somerset, Wiltshire), Hacche in South Molton (Devon), or else a topographic name from residence near a hatch, a gate leading to a forest or sometimes a sluice-gate, from Middle English <i>hacche</i> ‘gate’ (Old English <i>hæcce</i>, Kentish Old English <i>hec(c)</i>). This name has been in Ireland since the 17th century, associated with County Meath and the nearby part of Louth."],"variants":[{"name":"Hedge","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a hedge or enclosure, from Middle English <i>hegge</i> ‘hedge, fence’. In the early Middle Ages, hedges were not merely dividers between fields, but had an important defensive function when planted around a settlement or enclosure.","English: probably also a variant of   Hatch  , with voicing of the final consonant.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Hecke  ."]},{"name":"Hatcher","meanings":["English (southern): topographic name for someone who lived by a gate, from Middle English <i>haccher(e)</i>, a derivative of <i>hacche</i> ‘gate’. This normally denoted a gate marking the entrance to a forest or other enclosed piece of land, sometimes a floodgate or sluice-gate. Compare   Hatch  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Hatch was born in 1278, in Hatch, Somerset, England, United Kingdom as the son of John Hatch. He had at least 1 son with Joane Wolrington. He died in 1330, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1278–1330":"1278–1330","1277–Female":"1277–Surnud","1280–1298":"1280–1298","1298–1371":"1298–1371","1299–Male":"1299–Surnud","1245–1300":"1245–1300","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1299":"1299","1277":"1277","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1371":"1371","1280":"1280","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Aller, Dorset, England":"Aller, Dorset, England"},"fi":{"1278–1330":"1278–1330","1277–Female":"1277–Kuollut","1280–1298":"1280–1298","1298–1371":"1298–1371","1299–Male":"1299–Kuollut","1245–1300":"1245–1300","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1299":"1299","1277":"1277","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1371":"1371","1280":"1280","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Aller, Dorset, England":"Aller, Dorset, England"},"fr":{"1278–1330":"1278–1330","1277–F